<h2 id="sec-6" style="font-size:1.5em; font-weight:700; margin:2.5em 0 0.6em 0; color:#1a202c;">What is "binding"?</h2>

<img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/dmrekfwpj/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/tiktok-academy/shop/lesson-01/slides/slide-07.png" alt="" style="width:100%; display:block; margin:1.5em 0; border-radius:8px; box-shadow:0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.08);" />

<p style="line-height:1.7; color:#2d3748;">"Binding" is the word TikTok uses when you officially link your creator account to an agency — in this case, Creator Scans. It's basically saying: "this agency is my designated partner for TikTok Shop." It creates an <strong>exclusive relationship</strong> for Shop content, the contract sets out how long and how the commission splits work, and — crucially — you can <strong>unlink</strong> if you ever need to switch. You're part of the team, but you're not trapped.</p>

<h2 id="sec-7" style="font-size:1.5em; font-weight:700; margin:2.5em 0 0.6em 0; color:#1a202c;">The TAP advantage</h2>

<img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/dmrekfwpj/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/tiktok-academy/shop/lesson-01/slides/slide-08.png" alt="" style="width:100%; display:block; margin:1.5em 0; border-radius:8px; box-shadow:0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.08);" />

<p style="line-height:1.7; color:#2d3748;">This is why binding maths out. TAP (TikTok Affiliate Partner) is a marketplace where brands post campaigns with <strong>higher commission rates that are only available to agency-bound creators</strong>. Independent creators literally cannot see these deals. As an example: a brand might offer 10% commission on its public listing, but 17% on the same product through a TAP campaign. That's a <em>70% pay rise</em> on the exact same sale, just because you're bound. Over a year of consistent selling, that gap becomes huge.</p>

